        <tr> 
          <td align="center" height="34"> 
            <h2>Methane News</h2>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td valign="top"> 
            <p><i><img src="images/baabaa.jpg" width="100" height="100" align="left" alt="sheep"> 
              11th October </i><a href="http://www.nature.com/nclimate/journal/v7/n10/full/nclimate3403.html"><b>Mulling 
              Methane </b></a><br>
              Patrick Crill and Brett Thornton, of Stockholm University, have 
              reviewed the current state-of-the-art on methane science. They highlight 
              emerging knowledge on its sources and sinks around the world.</p>
            <p><i><img src="images/biogas.jpg" width="100" height="100" align="left" alt="fire"> 
              30th November 2013 </i><a href="http://www.nature.com/nclimate/journal/v3/n12/full/nclimate2034.html"><b>Short 
              and Sweet</b></a><br>
              Neil Bowerman and colleagues at the University of Oxford, UK, have 
              assessed the climate change mitigation potential of reducing emissions 
              of methane and black carbon.</p>
            <p><i><img src="images/greenstream.jpg" width="100" height="100" align="left" alt="stream"> 
              26th April 2013 </i><a href="http://www.nature.com/nclimate/journal/vaop/ncurrent/full/nclimate1864.html"><b>Greenhouse 
              Feedbacks</b></a><br>
              Ben Stocker and colleagues at the University of Bern have predicted 
              that climate change induces significant positive feedbacks in emissions 
              of both methane and nitrous oxide.</p>
            <p><i><img src="images/ricemethane.jpg" width="100" height="100" align="left" alt="rice"> 
              29th October 2012 </i><a href="http://www.nature.com/nclimate/journal/vaop/ncurrent/full/nclimate1712.html"><b>Rice 
              Methane Feedback</b></a><br>
              Kees Jan van Groeningen of Trinity College Dublin and colleagues 
              in the US, have projected an increase in methane emissions from 
              rice cultivation in response to future climate change.</p>
          </td>
        </tr>
